Here’s a concise, safe way to translate your calm print rhythm into a web layout.  
You can drop this CSS into a simple HTML page and it will create that sense of space and soft pacing:

```css
body {
  font-family: "Georgia", "Libre Baskerville", serif;
  font-size: 18px;
  line-height: 1.7;
  color: #272522;
  background-color: #faf8f6;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 3em 1.5em;
}

.entry {
  max-width: 650px;
  margin: 0 auto 5em auto;   /* breathing space between entries */
}

.entry h2 {
  font-size: 1.2em;
  letter-spacing: 0.02em;
  margin-bottom: 0.4em;
}

.interlude {
  font-style: italic;
  margin: 2em 2em;
  opacity: 0.8;
  border-left: 2px solid #dfdad3;
  padding-left: 1em;
}

hr {
  border: none;
  height: 1px;
  background-color: #dfdad3;
  margin: 3em 0;
}

.final-line {
  text-align: center;
  font-style: italic;
  margin-top: 5em;
  color: #44413e;
}
```

And in your HTML you could structure each section like:

```html
<article class="entry">
  <h2>Entry 1 – Noise</h2>
  <p>The hum from the vent feels louder than usual...</p>
  <p class="interlude">Two evenings pass; the hum in the vents softens...</p>
</article>
<hr/>
<article class="entry">
  <h2>Entry 2 – Light</h2>
  ...
</article>
<p class="final-line">The hum is still there; I’ve learned its tune.</p>
```

This keeps the reader’s eye moving slowly, gives every section its own “breathing room,” and visually differentiates the interludes without bright or distracting contrast.  
