Yes — a few small, responsive touches will make it read comfortably on any screen without changing your quiet pacing.  
You can add these rules to the end of your **quiet.css** file:

```css
/* Basic mobile adjustments */
@media (max-width: 700px) {
  body {
    font-size: 17px;
    line-height: 1.75;
    padding: 2em 1em;
  }

  .entry {
    margin-bottom: 4em;
  }

  .interlude {
    margin: 1.5em 1em;
    border-left-width: 1px;
  }
}

/* Larger tablets / desktops with wide view */
@media (min-width: 1200px) {
  body {
    font-size: 19px;
  }
  .entry {
    max-width: 720px;
  }
}
```

This makes the layout:

* **Readable on phones** — slightly smaller text with wider line spacing and relaxed side padding, so the columns don’t feel cramped.  
* **Balanced on wide screens** — a comfortable width and a touch more type size, keeping the same tranquil rhythm with generous margins.

You can preview by resizing your browser window; the text should always feel centered and airy.  

