Here are a few optional touches that give your page a little polish without breaking its stillness.

---

### **1 · Soft fade divider**
Instead of the solid line, you can add a gentle gradient so each section shift feels like a breath.

```css
hr {
  height: 1px;
  border: none;
  background: linear-gradient(to right,
              transparent, #d8d3cc 40%, transparent);
  margin: 3em 0;
}
```

---

### **2 · Automatic light / dark theme**
Modern devices report whether the user prefers dark or light. A simple media query can swap colors quietly:

```css
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  body {
    background-color: #1d1c1a;
    color: #e8e3de;
  }
  hr {
    background: linear-gradient(to right,
                transparent, #4b4742 40%, transparent);
  }
  .interlude {
    border-left-color: #4b4742;
  }
}
```

The result: pale text on a soft charcoal background—still low‑contrast, still calm.

---

### **3 · Accessible font contrast and focus**
Subtle tweaks that help readability but keep the tone quiet:

```css
a {
  color: #6c645b;
  text-decoration: underline dotted;
}
a:focus,
a:hover {
  color: #a09386;
  outline: none;
}
```

Even if your piece doesn’t have links now, this keeps the palette gentle for any future navigation or credit links.

---

### **4 · Optional scroll behavior**
A light “snap” between entries keeps the reader from rushing.

```css
html {
  scroll-behavior: smooth;
}
.entry {
  scroll-snap-align: start;
}
body {
  scroll-snap-type: y mandatory;
}
```

Each scroll stops neatly at a new entry—ideal for mobile viewing.

---

